Website Pages:
/register
/login
/profile: Display the user's info, and allowing the modification of these info
/predict: Allow the user to fill a form, then redirect the data into the ML module, then display the results
/history: If a normal user is logged in, it would display the user's prediction history,
           but an admin would have access to all users' history
/admin: Allows the admin to delete or promote a user (to an admin),
         also giving them the overall stats of predictions

DB Tables:
Users [id, firstName, lastName, age, gender, email, password, role("user", "admin"), created_at]
History [id, user_id, input_data(JSON), prediction_res, probability, date]

Python Module:
- Leave it for later

Code Flow:
- User sends a GET request to one of the pages, and gets the JSP
- For register, the user has to fill a form then POST request it to the server,
 which will verify the credentials and save them into the DB
- For login, same as register, the difference is that the login page asks for only email and password
- Profile page should be simple, a GET request to the server, which will return
 (if the request is valid) the user's info, and a POST request to update the user's info
- Predict page, makes the user fill a form (with data that we need to do a prediction),
 then sending it to the server, which will do a REST request to the Python server,
 get the prediction result, then store the result in the DB (for history),
 after that it will return the prediction to the user
- History page should be simple as well, the server will verify the privilege of the user,
 then query the DB and return the results
- In the Admin page, send a DELETE request to delete a user, a POST request to promote users,
 a GET request to get prediction stats, which will be used to create graphs
 and dashboards using a JS library

Notes:
- The hardest parts in this project would be training the model (getting the dataset
 and writing the training code itself), also authentication won't be easy
 (the method the server would use to know if the user has access to the data or not,
 and what their privilege is)
